english:
  title: Record of the Manjusri Monastery at Cheongpyeong Mountain
  author: Kim Bu-cheol
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Cheongpyeong Mountain in Chunju was formerly known as Gyeongwun Mountain, and the Manjusri Monastery was once called the Bodhisattva Monastery. The Zen master Yeong-hyeon came from Tang to Silla, and in the eighteenth year after the founding king's reign—the year of Eulmi—when Silla's King Gyeongshun surrendered his realm, it was the second year of Later Tang's Qingwu era. In the twenty-fourth year of King Gwangjong's reign, the master first arrived at Gyeongwun Mountain and founded a temple called the White Rock Zen Monastery. This was the sixth year of Song's Kaibao era. In the twenty-third year of King Munjong's reign, the year Musin, when the former official Yi, who served as Minister of Scattered Cavalry and Director of the Bureau of Military Affairs, came as supervisor of the granaries in Chunju, he fell in love with Gyeongwun Mountain's sublime beauty and built a temple on the site of White Rock, naming it the Bodhisattva Monastery. This was the first year of Xining era. Later, a recluse named Hee-i abandoned his post and withdrew to this place, and thereafter thieves ceased and tigers disappeared. The mountain was thus renamed Cheongpyeong. Moreover, having twice witnessed the manifestation of Manjusri Bodhisattva and received divine guidance on the essential teachings, the monastery was renamed Manjusri and further restored. This Hee-i was the eldest son of Minister Yi, named Ja-hyeon with the courtesy name Jeong-jeong. He possessed striking appearance and a naturally tranquil temperament. In the sixth year of Yuanfeng, he passed the civil service examination and became a high-ranking official. In the fourth year of Yuanyou, serving as a minor official in the Bureau of Music, he abandoned his post to escape worldly life. Journeying to Imjin River, as he crossed the waters he made a vow to himself: "From this crossing forward, I shall never return to the capital."

    His learning was comprehensive, yet he devoted himself especially to the profound principles of Buddhism, favoring in particular the practice of seated meditation. He often recounted how, upon reading the discourse of Master Xuefeng—"The entire universe is but one eye; where do you sit?"—he suddenly experienced sudden awakening. From that moment, he harbored no doubt toward the Buddha's teachings.

    He subsequently wandered throughout the Eastern lands' sacred mountains, seeking traces of ancient sages. Later, encountering National Master Huejao who presided over Hwaaak Temple on a neighboring mountain, he frequently consulted on the principles of Zen. Living on the mountain, he sustained himself on vegetables and hemp robes, finding joy in frugality and purity. Beyond the monastery, in a secluded valley, he constructed a private retreat, with more than a dozen structures including meditation halls and pavilions—a hall named "Hearing Nature," a hermitage called "Seeing Nature," and others such as "Immortal Grotto Hermitage," each bearing its own name. Daily he wandered among them in solitude. Sometimes he would sit alone through sleepless nights; sometimes he would remain on stone for entire days without returning; sometimes he would enter deep meditation in the Seeing Nature Hermitage for seven days before emerging.

    He once told his disciples: "I have exhausted the Buddhist canon and surveyed all teachings, yet the Shurangama Sutra stands foremost—it seals the mind's essence and illuminates the essential path. Yet few students of Zen have read it. What cause for lamentation!" He thus instructed his disciples to study it, and their numbers grew steadily.

    King Seongjong twice sent imperial envoys bearing tea, incense, and gold-threaded silk, commanding him to the palace. Yet the master, unwilling to betray his initial vow made crossing the river, refused the imperial summons. In the seventh year of Zhenghe, when the king traveled to the Southern Capital, the master's younger brother, the Minister of Works, was sent to request his attendance. The king composed a poem in his own hand and sent it:

    "I have long desired to see you,
    And as days pass, this longing grows.
    How can one move the will of a great sage?
    Yet what shall I do with this yearning heart?"

    The master submitted a memorial declining, but the king's earnest resolve could not be dissuaded. In the eighth month of that year, the master traveled to the Southern Capital to meet the king. The king said: "I have long admired this virtuous elder—how could I receive him with mere courtly protocol?" He commanded the master to ascend the palace hall and perform obeisance, then answered with obeisance himself. They sat together, took tea, and conversed at leisure. The king commanded him to stay temporarily at Cheongryangsa Temple on Samgak Mountain, whence he would frequently visit to inquire into Zen teachings. The master thereupon composed an essay on the essential principles of mind and presented it. Soon after, he earnestly requested to return to the mountain. The king bestowed upon him tea, incense, implements, and robes to honor his departure, and the queen and princesses also sent gifts of silk.

    By the third year of Xuanhe, the Minister again came bearing the king's command, establishing a major Shurangama lecture assembly in the mountains, which attracted scholars from all regions who came to listen and receive instruction. In the fourth year, the new king ascended the throne and specially sent the imperial attendant Yi Bong-won to offer respectful inquiries, presenting tea, incense, and clothing. By the seventh year, the master fell somewhat ill, and the court sent an imperial physician and medicines.

    The master had already chosen his burial site. One day he told his disciples: "My time is short. After my death, let my disciple Jo-won continue as abbot of this monastery. After Jo-won, choose those of virtue and integrity to succeed in succession."

    On the twenty-first day of the fourth month that year, he again addressed his disciples: "Human life is impermanent—we are born only to die. Do not grieve; keep your minds on the Way." Having spoken, at the hour of Shen he entered nirvana. At the moment of passing, his mind remained clear and undisturbed, speaking and smiling as in life. When he entered final rest, an extraordinary fragrance filled the chamber, gradually spreading throughout the mountain valleys, lingering for three days without ceasing. His entire body remained pure and white as jade, his limbs flexible as if alive. On the twenty-third day, the funeral rites were conducted entirely according to his wishes. From the fourth year of Yuanyou to the seventh year of Xuanhe, he dwelt on the mountain for seventeen years, reaching the age of sixty-five. In the eighth month of autumn in the fourth year of Jianyan, the court specially conferred upon him the posthumous title "Master of True Joy."

    Among his writings are collected poems in response to the "One Hundred Joys" of Master Baekryak, a volume of poems from his southern travels, a record of Zen dialogues, a collection of hymns, and a eulogy of the Laughing Buddha.

    Reflecting upon this: Since ancient times, many have lived as recluses—yet commonly these were disgraced ministers or forgotten men, without prospect in the world. Some began content in mountains but later compromised their principles. That one born to royal kinship and power should spend a lifetime in seclusion—this is rarely heard. Yet this master, wielding wealth and fame, achieving high office through his talents, was one for whom advancement through ranks was as easy as picking grass. He cast aside riches like worn sandals, regarded his very existence as passing clouds, and withdrew to the mountains never to return to court. Is this not extraordinary? Moreover, his clan had been imperial in-laws for generations, among the foremost families of the Three Realms, yet he alone transcended worldly dust, untouched by its constraints, his virtue and reputation only deepening. Not merely did the discerning admire and sigh at his example—even villagers and farmers, upon hearing of his virtue, could not but love and revere him. For when one instructs others through loyalty and serves all with sincerity, the profound influence reaches even spirits and heaven. Is this not why thieves ceased and tigers vanished from his mountain?

    In antiquity, Liang Hong who entered Baling Mountain was surely a worthy recluse, yet his wife Meng Guang shared his concealment. Pang Gong, dwelling on the southern slope of Xian Mountain and never entering the city, nonetheless kept his family near. How different from this master, who forgot all attachment to desire and released his body into the void! Tranquil and pristine, he tasted what ordinary people cannot taste, and from beginning to end remained unshaken—his lofty integrity unmoved by circumstance, his clear spirit eternally illuminating hearts. Truly he was a great recluse of ancient or modern times—perhaps the sole exemplar of the age.

    His disciple Jo-won brought the master's biography and earnestly requested that I write this record. Given the sincerity of his request, I have done so, relating here the complete account of the master's life and accomplishments. As for Cheongpyeong Mountain's waters, valleys, and sublime vistas—truly among the Eastern realm's most beautiful places—these I leave for a master of letters to celebrate in verse.
  footnotes:
    - The reference to 'Xuefeng's discourse' ('汝向甚處蹲坐') represents a famous Zen koan used to provoke sudden enlightenment by questioning the locus of awareness itself.
    - The Shurangama Sutra (首楞嚴經) was considered by Korean and Chinese Buddhist scholars of this period as fundamental to understanding the nature of consciousness and the path to enlightenment.
    - The detail about the master's body remaining 'pure and white as jade' with limbs flexible after death reflects Korean Buddhist hagiographic conventions suggesting spiritual achievement and transcendence.
    - The posthumous title 'Master of True Joy' (眞樂公) encodes the master's name Ja-hyeon (資玄) and reflects the court's recognition of his spiritual attainment.
